Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden changes in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely, because following the crisis, the global economy is imbalanced in many respects, particularly from the perspective of sovereign debts and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are the source of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect reliably and even more difficult to prove.
Secondly, predicting the exact moment of the tipping point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed and when there is no credit available) is, and will undoubtedly remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are highly non-linear events that occur without warning signs.
The periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those least responsible for them.
If this pattern were to repeat, it could undermine confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could herald excessive regulations, state intervention, and a disengagement from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is turning into a sovereign debt crisis in advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can lead to a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by a deterioration of tax revenues and an increase in bailout expenditures.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" in advanced economies include non-discretionary countercyclical measures.
Undetected imbalances and systemic risks make fiscal policies that seem prudent in fact not prudent.
Spain, for example, had no fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
But his income and expenditures were largely determined by a housing bubble linked to very high debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is undoubtedly a typical example.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of liabilities through restructurings or inflation.
If systemic risks can cause this kind of sequential cascading imbalance, sovereign states must be attentive to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk and quickly taking corrective measures.
Detailed new legislative frameworks, focusing on capital requirements and leverage, transparency, ratings and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection, and resolution mechanisms will soon be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the probability and severity of systemic risks.
But this will in no way resolve the problem of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and heralding instability.
In addition to and complementing new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
Some politicians and prominent analysts, however, believe that such a system, aimed at identifying and containing systemic risks, is futile.
The incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex, constantly evolving global financial system make risk detection, according to them, either impossible or so error-prone that this effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are right, we must then accept that we will periodically be in a situation of financial and fiscal instability without being able to predict it in advance.
We should then also accept a much more cautious fiscal policy than the one we considered necessary just three years ago.
In the field of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists of rejecting a true proposition and the other is accepting a false proposition.
Let's call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be phrased in these terms: in the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors has the highest probable cost?
Opponents of prudent oversight of systemic risks have two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there are no reliable signs indicating a potentially increasing instability.
Looking for such a sign is a waste of time.
Instability occurs instantly.
But this position seems fallacious.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note of them.
However, it must be admitted that these warnings may not have been sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not predict the breaking point.
They were nevertheless undeniable signs.
The second position is that there are indeed warning signs, but that they are so unreliable that taking measures would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that AQF has a probably higher cost than RQV, because there are many false positive elements and/or the remedy is worse than the disease.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with AQF error.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so that the aggregated negative effect of reacting to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I am not convinced, for my part.
There may be a deeper tendency at work.
Whether in business or investments, decisions are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty and errors are frequent.
The default position of decision-makers in advanced countries, on the contrary, seems to be that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply rooted belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one believes that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refuse to act unless there are good reasons to do so.
But in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a downward slide is at best questionable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that policy responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least try the experiment, and to do so give responsibilities to a new institution, or an existing one, that has access to relevant information, that has sharp analytical skills at both the financial and macroeconomic levels, and that is relatively shielded from conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and could thus influence the perception of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the ability of the financial system to self-regulate.
